-------> SCRIPTURE (15min)

The gospel of Matthew is the first book of the new testament

Before we read the word, let's give some context about Matthew who was first called Levi before accepting the invitation of Jesus to become a disciple

Who was he, why did he write this book? Why is the book important?

Levi was a Jewish man who lived in the first century AD

He worked for Rome as a tax collector. He was a member of the Roman IRS whose job it was to collect taxes from Jewish people for the roman empire

Being a tax collector was actually quite a lucrative profession because you could take extra for personal profit

Acording to the gospels, Levi was actually very wealthy

Despite being wealthy and having a lucrative profession, he would have been considered to be a sinner and traitor by his community because of his work for the roman empire

Jesus approached Levi at his tax booth in Capernaum which was a bustling trade hub and said "follow me"

Hearing Jesus, Levi immediately left his tax booth and accepted the invitation

He left behind his lucrative but despised position as a tax collector, left behind his belongings and his life to become a disciple of Jesus

So a tax collector called Levi made a decision to leave a life of financial security and wealth for a life of service as Matthew, an apostle of Jesus

It was a swift conversion. A radial trajectory change that transforms the life of Matthew and the reason we are still reading his words today

Demonstrates the power of decision and the capacity of sinners to change the trajectory of their lives to follow Jesus anytime and regardless of their past behaviours

It's worth noting that it was common practice for converts to adopt new names as a way to symbolize their new life and identity

Among the 4 gospels (Matthew, Mark, Luke and John, Matthew’s gospel is the longest and most detailed gospel. As a tax collector, Matthew was trained in record keeping and was a skilled writer.

The early church actually used Matthew as the primary teaching document and most quoted gospel for discipleship

Chapter 1 verse 1: "The book of the geneology of Jesus Christ, the son of David, the son of Abraham"

It was Jewish tradition to keep extensive, detailed genealogies to establish a persons legitimacy and ingeritance rights

In chapter 1 verses 2-16, Matthew demonstrates Jesus' legitimacy and legal claim to the throne of David

Important to note here is that the gospel of Matthew was written to a Jewish audience

Addressing the lineage of Jesus through extensive genealogy was important to demonstrate his royal lineage as a descendant of Abraham and David

This makes Jesus the rightful legal heir to the covenant promises associated with David and Abraham in the eyes of Jews for whom matthew wrote his gospel

